2. The European Context. Migration in and from Austria-Hungary, 1850–1914

2. The European Context.
Migration in and from Austria-Hungary, 1850–1914

Franz Omischl, an eleven year old boy from West-Hungary, arrived in the US in 1926, accompanied by his mother and sister, who both were called Pauline. At Ellis Island, the little family was welcomed by their husband and father, also called Franz. This was not his first journey; he and his parents had made multiple moves before crossing the Atlantic. Omischl’s father was born in Szentgotthárd/Monošter/St. Gotthard in the county of Vas/Eisenburg/Železna županija and as a young man moved to Budapest, where he found work as a waiter. There he met Pauline from Hodis (Markt Neuhodis)/Városhodász/Novi Hodas in Vas County, who was employed in a restaurant as well. The young couple got married in Hodis in 1912. After the wedding, the family moved to Rogaška Slatina/Rothirsch-Sauerbrunn, a spa town in Southern Styria (today in Slovenia), where they bought a restaurant. After the First World War, when the economic situation got worse in the 1920s, the family decided to move to Chicago, where relatives and former Hungarian neighbors provided a social network for the newcomer. Once in Chicago, the Omischl family settled in a neighborhood called “Humboldt Park” with many migrant neighbors, mostly Lithuanians and Russian Jews. The neighborhood to the east was called “West Town;” it had a sizable Hungarian migrant population in the 1920s. As the main breadwinner, the father got a job as a cook in a Chicago restaurant. The father Omischl died in 1951, while Franz, his son lived a long life and was buried in Chicago at the age of 89 years.1 The migration story of this family included places like small towns in Western Hungary, Budapest, Southern Styria, and later on a transatlantic move to Chicago, which was not untypical for mobile inhabitants of Austria-Hungary.
An additional story illustrates the transnational lives of migrants from Central and Eastern Europe, back and forth to America. In a recent study on migration patterns of Poles before and after the First World War, Brian McCook offers a glimpse of a very mobile life-story:
In 1872, Walek was born into a Polish farming family living along the German-Russian frontier in the Prussian province of Poznań/Posen and at the age of 16 left his village to work in Saxony. By 1892, however, unemployment forced Walek to move elsewhere and, after returning home briefly, he decided to seek his fortune in America, settling in 1893 in Scranton, Pennsylvania, the industrial centre of the coal producing regions of northeastern Pennsylvania. In Scranton, Walek was able to find work as both a miner and an iron-worker and saved money to send home to relatives … After only two years, however, an economic downturn in the Scranton area forced Walek to leave and he returned home to Posen in 1895. Within a few weeks, he decided to leave for the Ruhr Valley and once there, found work as a miner and steel worker […] Eventually, Walek married a woman from his homeland and he returned home with enough money to buy land in 1906.2
For most of the twentieth century, migration scholars have studied the diverse fields of internal, continental, and overseas migration separately. However, most countries that have been the sources of large-scale transatlantic migration have also experienced significant levels of mobility within Europe, either internal or across international borders. The massive movement of over 50 million Europeans overseas before World War I was itself part of a still larger migration within Europe during the same period. In particular, studies often focused exclusively on transatlantic crossings and treated all migrants as part of a single migration stream. Our approach assumes a high interdependence among various patterns of human movements. Instead of treating transatlantic mobility as a uni-directional phenomenon, this chapter will demonstrate that in the late nineteenth century, Central European migrants had several destination choices: within their own country, to another European country, or to another continent.3 We treat transatlantic migration as an integral part of European spatial mobility as a whole.4
This chapter gives an overview of the multidirectional and seasonal nature and the repeated back-and-forth movements of local, continental, and transatlantic migration patterns in the history of late Imperial Austria-Hungary. Inhabitants of all districts and counties of Imperial Austria and the Hungarian Kingdom took part in numerous migration activities, thus providing a rich field for testing various patterns of regional mobility. The chapter is divided into three sections: First, we will describe the importance of internal migration; second, we will address seasonal, international, and transatlantic patterns and take a closer look at the choices people had when deciding to migrate. When considering migration decisions, we take the intention of returning into account since it informed the original plan to emigrate. Therefore, the third section will discuss the limited usefulness of terms such as “emigration” and “immigration,” given that up to 40 percent of Austrian-Hungarian migrants returned from the United States of America to Central Europe.
We offer the perspective that many – perhaps the majority – of regional movements were temporary rather than permanent, and that most migrants moved within the same state. Our analysis presents some new examples to this history. Although temporary and circular migration patterns are of special importance for European people in modern times, they were neglected by migration research for decades. In the 1980s, Jan Lucassen and Klaus Bade focused their studies on people who moved around Europe on a seasonal basis to find work, mostly in agriculture.5 According to these sources, spatial movements were not linear, restricted to a direct move from an origin to a destination point. As Leslie Page Moch recently pointed out, “Even during phases of rapid population growth and industrialization, for each stream of migrants, there is a counterstream back to origin”.6 European migrants had especially high turnover rates. Even during periods of intensified urbanization, one-time moves from the countryside to central cities were not predominant.7 Regional mobility took many different forms. At the same time, migration patterns consisted of various movements back and forth. The move may have been permanent from the perspective of the migrant – he or she may have left the home country permanently, but remained temporarily in more than one host region for long stretches of time, as in the story of the Omischl family. In the process of coping with their everyday lives, people moved around their home districts, sometimes crossed provincial borders or even made their way to the neighboring countries. For most people from Austria-Hungary, a transatlantic voyage was an exception until the end of the nineteenth century.8

Back and Forth within Austria-Hungary

In nineteenth century Central Europe, the majority of people moved short distances, to and from already established urban areas and newly developing industrial centers, as well as agrarian regions and rural communities. Contrary to the popular assumption that transatlantic movement was the dominant migration pattern from 1880 to the start of World War I, as early as 1902 Gustav Thirring’s work on migrants from the Hungarian Kingdom showed just the opposite.9 Working with census records, he calculated that between 1881 and 1900 exactly 1,034,203 people had left their place of birth, and more than half of them (654,228) migrated internally.10 Since censuses did not provide information on temporary seasonal migration, it may be assumed that internal migration was in fact even much higher.

Source: Österreichische Statistik 1912–1915; Volkszählung in den Ländern der ungarischen Krone 1910, Budapest 1924.
Note: Imperial Austria was divided into political districts, the Hungarian Kingdom in counties. Internal out-migration = percentage of the whole population of a district or county who have moved to another district or county inside Imperial Austria or the Hungarian Kingdom.
Beginning in the 1860s, Austria-Hungary’s population was allowed to move freely without any identification documents, even into other Western European countries and overseas. Only journeys to the Ottoman and Russian Empire required an official visa. Passports for internal travels were abolished in 1857, and the Constitution (Staatsgrundgesetz) of 1867 entitled every inhabitant to a free choice of residence. Simultaneously with the liberalization of free movement, however, the Austrian government expanded the observation of aliens and stepped up the use of deportation. The legislative right of domicile (Heimatrecht), which was passed in 1863, assigned each person to a certain locality. According to this law, the “hometown” was responsible for taking care of the elderly and the poor if no private support was available. Therefore, especially people from the lower strata of society could be restricted in their mobility, since, in case of impoverishment, they risked compulsory deportation to their domicile community.11
While population mobility was intensive, migration involved short distances. According to the 1910 census of Imperial Austria, 37.6 percent of the population had at least migrated beyond their home municipal boundaries, and nearly 25 percent had crossed the border of a political district, but only 8.6 percent moved across provincial borders and just 2.2 percent left the country.12 People from the Hungarian Kingdom seemed to be less mobile than Austrians. While in Imperial Austria 37.6 percent of the population lived somewhere other than their place of birth in 1910, in the Hungarian Kingdom this proportion was only 30 percent.13 On average, inhabitants of Imperial Austria tended to be more regionally mobile, but the rates varied across political districts. In the large province of Galicia, 79.2 percent of the people lived within the municipal boundaries of their birthplaces. On the other hand, the ratio of persistence was much lower in more industrialized parts, such as Lower Austria (47.2 percent) or Bohemia (55.3 percent).14 A study on migration patterns in nineteenth century Bohemia identified seven major political districts for overseas migration in the census returns of 1910. But even in these districts of strong overseas migration, internal migration was clearly far more important. In each of these districts, between 10,000 and 23,000 people had left their district of birth to settle somewhere else within Bohemia, while only 4,600 to 11,500 lived somewhere outside the province, but still within Imperial Austria.15
Urban centers were the most prominent areas of internal in-migration, as shown in figure 2.2. Larger cities, such as Vienna, Prague, Budapest, and Graz, acted as important points of attraction for migrants from Austria-Hungary. Budapest attracted the most in-migrants, but also smaller towns such as Timişoară/Temesvár (in present-day Romania) or Zagreb/Agram (now the capital of Croatia), were selected by in-migrants. After Prague, Vienna was the most important city that attracted migrants from the Bohemian territory; by contrast, most migrating Slovaks headed for Budapest.16
Figure 2.2: Spatial distribution of internal in-migration in Austria-Hungary, in 1910 (political districts and counties)

In the 1890s, Gustav Thirring, a Hungarian statistician, first spotted in the census returns regional movements from the Kingdom of Hungary to Croatia and Slavonia as an important internal migration pattern. Between 1880 and 1890, the number of inhabitants of the Kingdom of Croatia and Slavonia who were born in Hungary increased from 82,260 to 112,041.17 In the Hungarian Kingdom, internal migrants went predominantly from the northern parts of the territory to the south, with a clear preference for Budapest and its surroundings as their main destination. In the north, people from the counties of Heves, Nógrád, and Nitriansky Kraj/ Nyitra (in present-day Slovakia), as well as people from Fejér/Stuhlweiß County in the west, were most likely to move south. The Hungarian lowland plain proved to be highly attractive for internal migrants. Agriculture continued as the major economic activity into the early twentieth century in most counties with a Slovak-speaking majority. The migration of itinerant laborers for seasonal jobs to the central Hungarian plains continued as part of the Kingdom’s economic system.18 Long before the 1867 Ausgleich, a way of life based on migration had been established among Slovaks and Ukrainians.19 This migration pattern continued into the second half of the nineteenth century, with movements to industrial urban areas gaining importance at the end of the century. In 1910, about 300,000 people born in counties which are now part of Slovakia had moved to other parts of Hungary. According to Heinz Fassmann’s analysis, the population density in Hungarian counties more strongly correlated with internal migration than in Imperial Austria. In the Hungarian territories, internal mobility and urbanization seemed to be more closely linked than in the Austrian political districts, and networks of migration were more concentrated on the central region around Budapest.20
Whereas dominant regions of in-migration developed in both administrative halves of Austria-Hungary, inhabitants from the more distant areas at the borders preferred different routes. Internal out-migration rates were significantly lower in the Austrian east, in the provinces of Galicia and Bukovina, in the south-eastern Hungarian territories of Transylvania and Banat and in the south, in most parts of the Kingdom of Croatia and Slavonia, and in the district of Dalmatia. People from these border territories cannot be described as more sedentary or geographically persistent, but instead they took part in other continental and transatlantic migration processes. They most often crossed national frontiers to neighboring countries or found their way to other continents.

Migration between Imperial Austria and the Kingdom of Hungary

People from Imperial Austria as well as from the Hungarian Kingdom crossed the borders to the other side. A study of the Kingdom Hungary’s census records, together with church records maintained in Hungary and the United States, shows that on the northern ridge of the Carpathians, which divided Galicia from Hungary, there was considerable movement of people back and forth over the mountain passes.21 Four Austrian provinces bordered Hungary on the north and east: Moravia, Austrian Silesia, Galicia, and Bukovina. On the west, another five provinces shared borders with the Hungarian Kingdom: Lower Austria, including the capital of Vienna, Styria, Littoral, Carniola, and Dalmatia.
By far the largest group of Austrian-born people living in Hungary originated in Galicia. According to contemporary observations, movements of Galician seasonal workers to Hungary and further on to Romania started around the 1890s.22 Even if censuses do not provide information on seasonal migration, an analysis of the growing number of Galician-born people living in Hungary indicates an increase of attractiveness of the Kingdom as a migration destination (see figure 2.3). From 1870 to 1910, the number of Galician-born people living in the Kingdom of Hungary increased more than tenfold; the female ratio of this migration pattern rose from 31 percent in 1870 to 46 percent. Galician migrants in Hungary were concentrated in Budapest and a handful of counties along the Carpathian frontier, such as Zemplín/Zemplen, Spiš/Szepes, and Šariš/Sáros (all three counties now part of Slovakia).
Figure 2.3: Galician-born people, living in the Hungarian Kingdom, 1870–1910
Source: Magyar Központi Statisztikai Hivatal. A Magyar Szent Korona Országainak 1910-evi. Népszámlálása, Budapest 1916, Table 5. “A külföldi honosok részletezése.”
Movements from Imperial Austria to the Kingdom of Hungary were not limited to Galician inhabitants. In 1910, nearly 20 percent of all Austrian migrants originated in the province of Bohemia, followed by 15 percent from Moravia. Hungary’s relatively late industrialization (as compared to parts of Imperial Austria) and a growing demand for skilled laborers in the new industrial centers, especially Budapest, led to an in-migration of mainly Czechs and Jews from the Bohemian Lands. Moravia was the main recruitment area with 51.5 percent of all qualified foreign workers.23
According to the Hungarian historian László Varga, the Jewish population of the Hungarian Kingdom rose from 126,620 people in 1805 to nearly one million in 1910 due to heavy in-migration from Austrian provinces. Its proportion in the population of the Kingdom peaked at 4.6 percent in 1869, and then leveled off at that number through the end of the Habsburg Monarchy. He distinguished three different Jewish migration patterns in the nineteenth century. In 1850, more than 77,000 of the Jewish people living in Hungarian territories were Galician-born. Even more people from western Galicia and Austrian Silesia crossed the mountains in the second half of the nineteenth century and settled overwhelmingly in the countries of Orava/Árva/Arwa, Liptov/Liptó/Liptau, and Trencsén (in present-day Slovakia). A third group of Jewish migrants who had moved to Hungarian territories originated in Moravia.24 The Jewish population was especially concentrated in the Hungarian counties that made up the long frontier with the Austrian provinces of Galicia and Moravia, areas that had a majority of Slovak- and Ukrainian-speaking populations.
According to marriage records for the synagogues of Šariš county on the Carpathian frontier, of the 753 total marriages listed between 1867 and 1939, 617 give the place of birth or place of residence of the groom at the time of marriage. As many as three-quarters of the grooms for whom a birthplace or place of residence is known, came from counties within the Kingdom of Hungary, usually Šariš or elsewhere in the Felvidék. However, one-quarter of the grooms traveled from outside the Kingdom to find a bride in Šariš. For these non-Hungarian grooms, Galicia was overwhelmingly their place of birth or residence. The wedding dates indicate that the decades of 1880–1889 and 1890–1899 saw the most weddings between Galician grooms and Šariš brides.25 This trans-Carpathian movement of Jewish men preceded the great migration of Šariš Jews from the county to the US, peaking in the years 1903–1907.26
During the second half of the century, this migration pattern reversed, and more and more Jewish people moved from Hungarian territories to Imperial Austria, especially to Vienna. The Viennese Jewish population increased considerably after the decree of 1860, which allowed Jews to acquire property, and after the inter-confessional equalization of 1868, which granted Jewish citizens of Imperial Austria the same legal rights as Christians. Already in 1857, about a quarter of all Jewish inhabitants in Vienna were born in Hungarian territories; most of them were short-distance migrants from Bratislava.27 Nearly 28 percent of all Viennese Jews (72,588) who were recorded in the census of 1880 originated in the Kingdom of Hungary, and by 1910, about a fifth of all Hungarian migrants in Imperial Austria were Jewish.28
At the end of the nineteenth century, a higher number of people from the Hungarian territories moved west to the Austrian provinces because Imperial Austria provided better-paying jobs for these migrants. The number of Hungarian-born people living in Imperial Austria rose from 53,000 in 1857 to 324,000 in 1900, at the same time raising the ratio of Hungarian migrants among all foreigners from 44.5 to 51.6 percent in 1910.29 Most of the migrants originated in counties of western Hungary bordering Imperial Austria, and the overwhelming majority moved short distances; nearly 70 percent chose Vienna as their destination.30 Besides Lower Austria, Styria, whose capital Graz was the most attractive spot for migrants, also received many Hungarians.31 The Austrian census of 1910 estimated that about 92,000 people were born in counties with a Slovak-speaking majority. Additionally, each year numerous Slovak seasonal agricultural workers migrated to Lower Austria.32

Migration is a Multidirectional Phenomenon

Although various migration patterns within, from, and to Austria-Hungary had a long-standing history, transatlantic movements were not a characteristic feature of mass mobility prior to the 1880s. In comparison with other European regions such as western Germany or the Scandinavian countries, inhabitants of the Habsburg Monarchy were latecomers to transatlantic migration. Although some people from provinces of Imperial Austria had started moving to North America as early as the eighteenth century, a new type of overseas traffic emerged in the decades preceding World War I.33 Even though few restrictions on emigration from the Habsburg Monarchy existed, transatlantic migration was rather limited in scope until the 1850s. According to official surveys, only 14,255 people left the Austrian provinces for destinations overseas between 1821 and 1830; from 1831 to 1840, the total was 7,536 people. These low numbers changed between 1851 and 1860: The figures for transcontinental migrants from Austria-Hungary suddenly climbed to 27,045, with the United States as the major destination (83 percent).34 By the first decade of the twentieth century, Austria-Hungary had become a major source of labor migrants to the US.
Approximately 15 million people left Europe for the US in the period from 1890 to 1914, and the vast majority of them had been born in Eastern and Southern Europe. The records of US immigration authorities show people from Austria-Hungary to be the largest single group among new arrivals between 1902 and 1911, with 27.9 percent of all US-bound migrants, followed by migrants from the Kingdom of Italy and the Russian Empire.35 With the start of World War I, the great transatlantic movements of central Europeans declined sharply.
However, most countries that have been the source of large-scale overseas migration also experienced significant migration within their borders and to other European countries. Preceding World War I, the East formed the greatest reservoir of cheap laborers for the growing industry of Western Europe as well as for commercialized agriculture.36 During the late nineteenth century, Central Europeans had a variety of migration choices available to them: within one’s country, to another European country, or to another continent.
People from the provinces of Bohemia and Moravia started to choose among these different migration paths by the middle of the nineteenth century. From 1850 to 1914, 1.6 million people emigrated from the Czech Lands. International migration from Bohemia seems to have been important during the whole nineteenth century, whereas internal rural-urban migration reached a first peak in the 1870s.37 From 1900 to 1913, Bohemian out-migrants outnumbered in-migrants by as many as 500,000.38 As the province formed the industrial core of Austria-Hungary, the extent of net out-migration is astonishing. The Bohemian territories were responsible for over 70 percent of Imperial Austria’s manufacturing production in 1910.39 Besides the transatlantic passage, other destinations existed, especially Vienna and its surrounding areas, as well as the German Reich; even the Russian Empire attracted Austrian migrants. Bohemians clearly dominated the group of foreign laborers in the heavily industrialized border region of Saxony; in 1907, more than 99,000 of Saxony’s inhabitants had been born in Bohemia.40 A contemporary estimate that drew on the 1910 census found that about 330,000 people born in Bohemia were living in another European country, with about two thirds of them in the German Reich, compared to about 183,000 who were reported in the US for the same year.41
Another long-standing tradition of border-crossings existed in the westernmost part of the Monarchy, in the provinces of Tyrol and Vorarlberg, where each spring labor migrants, many of them children (so-called Schwabenkinder), headed to Southwestern German regions.42 The province of Vorarlberg was a center for both in- and out-migration, with target regions such as Switzerland and France.43 Inhabitants of the Hungarian Kingdom also moved to different European countries, but only in the case of the German Reich, the Kingdoms of Romania and Serbia, and other Balkan states can we observe mass mobility.44 As early as 1876, the contemporary scholar Johann Hintz studied movements of Romanian-speaking people from Transylvania to the Kingdom of Romania, one of the well-established patterns of regional mobility.45 Romanians from the Hungarian Kingdom either migrated as seasonal agricultural laborers or as peddlers who marketed wooden products and other items, such as cheese and leather goods, in Romania, Bulgaria, and Bessarabia (present-day Republic of Moldova). Nearly half of these migrants to Romania were female. The movement of Romanian-speaking women from southeast Hungary to Bucureşti/Bucharest as domestic servants for middle class households also had a long tradition.46 In addition to Romanians, German-speaking people from Transylvania, the so called Siebenbürger Sachsen and Schwaben, moved as seasonal agricultural laborers to Wurttemberg and Hessen in the German Reich.47
According to the thematic maps in figures 2.1 and 2.2, inhabitants of the Austro-Hungarian border provinces and counties, from Galicia, Bukovina, Dalmatia, Croatia-Slavonia, and Transylvania, were less likely to take part in internal migration processes. Poles, Ukrainians, Slovaks, Croatians, Hungarians, Jews, and also German speakers from these regions took part in various other migrations across national frontiers within Europe and across the Atlantic Ocean. Results of the Austrian census for migration rates show that at the end of the nineteenth century, the small province of Carniola, in the south near the Mediterranean, had the highest international migration rates: 574 per 10,000 of its inhabitants left the Austrian territories between 1890 and 1900; Galicia was next with 416 migrants per 10,000 inhabitants. The province of Styria was located on the other end of this migration scale, with just 73 migrants per 10,000 people.48

Seasonal Migration Patterns in Austria-Hungary

A seasonal migration pattern between Bohemia and some German territories existed since the early modern period; there is even a special German term for it – Sachsengängerei.49 People, mainly from the northern parts of Bohemia, crossed the border to Saxony and Prussia in search of farm work. Agricultural labor migration from the southwestern districts of Bohemia to the Kingdom of Bavaria was noted as early as the second half of the seventeenth century.50 Galician migrants started to seek seasonal work in German agriculture comparatively late, at the end of the nineteenth century.51 During the 1890s, the number of labor migrants in the German Reich grew rapidly with Galicia as the main province of origin.52 Broad changes in agricultural production resulted in rising demand for seasonal day laborers in Western and Central Europe. The use of newly invented engines, such as threshing machines, changed farming from land-extensive to capital-intensive production methods. This change to a more industrialized agriculture was accompanied by the cultivation of new crops, especially sugar-beets.53 Both changes, the use of machines and the mass cultivation of sugar-beets, intensified the need for short-term laborers during periods of harvest. Since large numbers of agricultural laborers were only needed for short peak periods during sowing and harvesting, most land owners (both manorial lords and peasants) employed hired workers only on short contracts. The growing seasonal demand resulted in increasing rates of regional mobility of male and female agricultural workers.
A good example of a survey on seasonal labor migration is given by the statistics presented by the Bohemian administration in 1913.54 Information on 117,698 seasonal migrants survived from some political districts. The regional centers of seasonal labor migration in Bohemia were in the south and the west of the province. At the end of the nineteenth century, seasonal farm work was mainly dominated by people from Galicia, because Bohemians preferred employment in industry, trade, and mining. Between 1906 and 1914, about 90 percent of all Czech-speaking migrants in the German province of Prussia were engaged in industry.55 Only a small proportion of migrants from the Czech territories worked in agriculture. Before the First World War, many male Bohemians worked as brick makers, while women dominated in the textile industry of Saxony. The most important internal system of seasonal labor migration was the annual movement of thousands of harvest workers every August to the hop-growing region of Žatec/Saaz in central Bohemia west of Prague. In addition, about 2,500 Bohemians crossed the border to Bavaria to work in the hop fields as well.56
At the end of the nineteenth century, more and more migrants were searching for work in new industrial enterprises, even as agriculture remained the major employer for mobile laborers. The German Reich led this shift. In 1907, more than half of all foreign laborers were engaged in industry, mining, and construction trade (440,800 or 57 percent of all foreigners employed); only 36 percent worked in agriculture, and the remainders were mainly merchants and artisans.57 Despite this general tendency, farming still provided most jobs for Galician men and women: 367,711 laborers from this Habsburg province worked on German fields, followed by 41,319 engaged in construction work.58 In response to the growing number of foreign seasonal workers, the German administration expelled all Polish-speaking Austrian and Russian citizens in 1885. Even though this law was changed again in 1890, only seasonal in-migration was allowed. At the end of every year, Polish workers from Austrian and Russian territories had to leave for several weeks.59
Not only regional but also occupational mobility characterized seasonal labor migrants from Austria-Hungary. In accordance with the needs of the labor market, wage laborers alternated between agriculture and factory employment. During one season, working in sugar beets was their main income; the following year, they could make a living in a factory or mine while still maintaining close ties to agriculture. Different sectors of the economy demanded different volumes of work; therefore, the periods of employment for seasonal laborers could vary between several weeks and ten months a year.60 Late nineteenth century Central Europeans were not simply either urbanites or rural bumpkins; they were not divided neatly into agriculturalists or industrial workers. While some agricultural enterprises offered only very short employment contracts during harvest seasons, other farm laborers stayed from sowing until harvesting with the same employer. The growing industry provided more stable employment, but some industrial workers followed seasonal frequencies regardless. Already in the late 1860s, inhabitants of the German Reich, who made their living in agriculture and factory work, had been described as “workers-peasants.”61
Let us recall the story of the farm boy Walek given at the beginning of this chapter: aside from going overseas, finding a job in the German Reich was the most prominent alternative for people from Austria-Hungary: 370,900 Austro-Hungarians were counted in German territories in 1900; this number rose to 622,655 in 1910.62 However, at the end of the nineteenth century, the German Reich was not the only European country seeking cheap seasonal laborers. France, Switzerland, and the Scandinavian countries also competed for foreign agricultural workers from Central and Eastern Europe. By the 1890s, Danish beet growers and sugar producers had begun importing people from Russian Poland and Galicia; in 1907, the number of labor migrants from these regions who found employment in Denmark rose to 6,600 people.63 By 1913, Denmark counted between 12,000 and 18,000 Polish labor migrants from Imperial Austria and the Russian Empire. The legal position of Poles in Denmark was significantly better than in Germany. Denmark legislated protection of the migrant status of Polish workers in 1908.64 At the beginning of the twentieth century, Swedish and Swiss sugar producers, as well as French beet growers, began competing for seasonal workers from all three of the Polish territories.65 Imre Ferenczi estimated that in 1910, the number of Galician seasonal workers in France was 40,000, while in the Netherlands, Denmark, Sweden, and Norway another 80,000 Polish and Ukrainian laborers from Austria-Hungary found employment.66 Within Europe, the international competition for migrant workers grew significantly, and recruitment was increasingly aggressive in areas on the outskirts of the agrarian capitalist centers. By 1910, even the Hungarian Kingdom competed with the German Reich for Galician seasonal workers.67

Multiple Directions from Western Galicia – a Case Study

During the first decade of the twentieth century, the Polish Roman Catholic Church conducted an inquiry of regional mobility among its Galician bishoprics. Since so many Poles were on the move, the church administration supposed that they were in need of religious guidance. On the one hand, the church officials wanted to make sure that these migrants were guided on their way by a Roman Catholic priest; on the other hand, the Polish Roman Catholic Church was interested in constructing new church buildings in major destination countries, where their members could attend mass celebrated by a Polish priest and be able to confess their sins in their mother tongue. Given the high number of Polish migrants at the turn of the century, the Roman Catholic Church was especially interested in their whereabouts.
Every priest was ordered to count the migrants among his parishioners and to complete a questionnaire with the following questions: How many Roman Catholic inhabitants of the community were regionally mobile? What paths did the migrants take? Did they migrate permanently or seasonally? Did single people leave the village or whole family units? What causes did the migrants give for their movements?68 The correspondence among the episcopal deaneries indicates the importance of religious guidance for migrating Poles. For example, a Polish priest writing to the bishop in Kraków/Krakau in 1908 emphasized the high and still growing number of thousands of Polish laborers in Budapest and requested the construction of a new Roman Catholic Church devoted to the Polish people.69

Table 2.1 is based on the migration survey of parishes in the diocese of Tarnów in the Western part of Galicia. Since the Roman Catholic Church showed only interest in their members, the regional mobility of other inhabitants of the community such as Jews, members of Orthodox Churches, Greek Catholics, or Protestants, were not included. In 1910, 46.5 percent of the Galician inhabitants were Roman Catholics; 42.1 percent, mostly Ukrainians, were members of the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church – a small minority of them (6.1 percent) belonged to the Ukrainian Eastern Church – and another 10 percent were Jewish.70 Since the diocese of Tarnów was mainly populated by Polish-speaking people, it can be estimated that the Catholic census captured the majority of all regionally mobile people in its territories.
At the beginning of the twentieth century, a large number of Galician inhabitants chose to go on a transatlantic journey, although alternative migration routes existed as well.71 People could either choose to move inside Austria-Hungary or they could head for another European country. Of course, some decided to remain at home and not to move at all.72 No clear picture can be gained by comparing different transatlantic migration rates. For example, from the parish of Mielec/Melitz, nearly 90 percent of the migrant population chose another continent as their destination, while, on the other hand, the overwhelming majority of mobile inhabitants of Wojnicz made their way to other European countries. But there were also parishes, such as Łącko/Lacko or Czchów/Weißenkirchen, where the destinations of the migrant people were nearly evenly split up between America and Europe.
In addition to the number of migrants who either stayed in Europe or went overseas, officials of the Polish Roman Catholic Church also asked for the European destinations. How often a region was mentioned serves as an indicator for the attractiveness of this destination. Besides the United States of America, the German Reich was the next important country for labor migrants; the German province of Prussia was leading the list of destinations with 67 entries. At the beginning of the twentieth century, according to the church survey, Denmark, which imported labor migrants from the Galician west, was the next important country. Likewise, Sweden was quite often given as a destination for migrants from the Habsburg east.73
A considerable number of Catholics from the diocese of Tarnów moved within Austria-Hungary; in 1907, priests from 23 parishes recorded that some of their members were headed for the Kingdom of Hungary. Within one parish, destinations could be scattered all over Western and Central Europe. For example, people from Dobra Poles moved as seasonal laborers to Austrian Silesia, to the Kingdom of Hungary, to Prussia or Saxony in the German Reich, while in the parish of Baranów the provinces of Poznań, Pomerania, Brandenburg, Silesia, Saxony, and Hannover in the German Reich were mentioned besides Denmark as regions where migrants were headed as seasonal laborers.74
While most historical migration research still favors an image of a few routes which dominated migration patterns, the western Galician example shows quite a different picture. Migration patterns of inhabitants of the Habsburg empire can hardly be described as uni-directional, i.e. moving from one point of origin to a destination region; instead, regional mobility was a multidirectional phenomenon.75 In fact, as our analysis shows, it might just have been the rule that one region was linked with various other regions via reciprocal movements.

And Back to Austria-Hungary

Migration routes have never been one-way streets. In the case of continental migration patterns – whether inside Austria-Hungary or beyond international borders – many migrations did not result in a permanent change of residence but had a temporary character. Even though one had to travel quite a long distance via ship to cross the Atlantic, and this journey often started with a long train ride, many transcontinental moves ended with the migrants coming back to Europe. Once Europeans started to settle in the Americas, some of the migrants began returning to their birth countries. From all areas of overseas settlements, people chose to head back, albeit the number of returnees varied according to different time periods.76
The subject of return migration and its social and economic consequences was and is a vital component in the story of human mobility, but it has only begun to attract serious attention from scholars in recent decades.77 Given the high number of return migrants, it is surprising that it has not created more interest among migration scholars. The cause of this might be that returnees have been viewed as “failures” in some way, people who had not adapted to their host country or culture.78 Similarly, migrants who moved closer to home were motivated by various factors, and they returned home for a number of reasons. Although some came back with their pockets empty, their health ruined, or their illusions shattered, not all of them were bankrupt, ailing, or disaffected. Some who had left home with no thought of returning changed their mind. A significant number, however, went overseas with no intention of settling permanently in the new environment, but with the goal of making money abroad and bringing it back to improve the economic situation of their families in Europe.79 Migrants who intended to return did not only base their decisions on immediate and future circumstances in the host economy, but also on expected future returns in their country of origin.80 Mark Wyman, who has done very impressive studies on return migrants, condensed five major reasons for migrants’ returning to where they came from: success or failure in the new home; homesickness; a call to return to take over the family farm or other property; rejection of integration into life overseas.81 Most often, their decisions depended on social relations. Family networks were highly influential when it came to migration. In addition, social networks could extend beyond the nuclear family, for example, as shown by Laurence Fountaine’s work on networks of kin and clientele in Alpine societies in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries.82 Likewise, their decisions were determined by family and extended social networks.
For those who left, migration could mean a new beginning in a new environment, but those who stayed behind often perceived a family member’s departure differently. Social and economic positions, formerly held by migrants, became vacant and had to be filled; much of the social configuration needed rearranging. Larger migration movements could lead to extensive social changes in the society of origin.83 Likewise, demographic consequences of regional mobility are still an under-researched area in historical studies. What happened to gender balances when either men or women were the dominant migration group?84 The ones left behind, for example, women with children, might have a harder time coping without a male breadwinner. Also, not all migrants managed to get (or keep) a decent job in the US, and they might not have been able to support their families at home. This situation could be worse if they did not know if the husband would return at all.85 Return migrants were not always welcomed with open arms by those who stayed and who might mistrust the new conceptions and broadened horizons of the returnees. To return to the example of the Polish migrant Walek, he found that after returning to Poznán, his experiences abroad aroused suspicion. Local village leaders, particularly priests, were generally upset by returning Poles’ penchant for challenging their traditional authority, which led to priests’ warning compatriots about the corrupt ways of westernized Poles.86 On the one hand, the sedentary or persisting population might treat migrants as “traitors” who had abandoned them; on the other hand, they personified the promise for a better future for the whole society. We have to be careful not to jump to conclusions about return migrants becoming future innovators.87
Increasing globalization in the labor market modified transcontinental migration patterns at the end of the nineteenth century. Whereas in the middle of the century, permanent resettlement still dominated transatlantic migration, more and more Europeans chose to move to the Americas as temporary labor migrants during the following decades.88 As transportation became more efficient due to the expansion of railways and steamships, trips between Europe and the Americas got faster and, even more importantly, much cheaper.89 The decision to leave could be taken more lightly because it was becoming relatively easy to return. If migrants had problems adjusting in the new country, they were able to return.
According to Dudley Baines’s studies, between a quarter and one-third of all late nineteenth century transatlantic European migrants returned. In addition, he emphasizes the significant influence of return migrants on the society in their native country.90 Between 1870 and 1914, on average, up to 40 percent of all transcontinental migrants from England and Wales returned to the British Isles. Likewise, more than 30 percent of people from Scotland (which was, besides Ireland and Norway, one of the countries with the highest number of overseas migrants per capita) returned from North America.91 Less than half of the Italians who left the south of their native country in the first decade of the twentieth century permanently settled in the United States, while the others traveled back to Europe.92 According to Adam Walaszek’s study on transatlantic labor migration of Poles, return migration was the primary intention of most of these people.93 Between 1908 and 1957, 15.7 million in-coming people were counted in the US, but at the same time, 4.8 million left the country.94
At the beginning of the twentieth century, married men frequently left their families in Europe and returned to them after a few years in the United States.95 Migrants from Austria-Hungary followed this pattern: leaving Europe in the hope of making more money in the US and coming back to a socially and economically improved future. For example, in 1902, the rate of people returning to the county of Liptov/ Liptó in the Hungarian Kingdom (in present-day Slovakia) has been estimated at 50 percent.96 A man named Branko Grado from Dalmatia is reported to have crossed the Atlantic seventeen times.97 Starting in 1908, US officials began tabulating the numbers of Europeans returning from the States. According to the records of the US Immigration Bureau, the rate of return migrants to Imperial Austria was 39.5 percent; the percentage of those going back to the Hungarian Kingdom was slightly lower (37.9 percent).98 Since the cost of living was much lower in early-twentieth-century Central Europe, it made sense economically for migrants to spend the money earned abroad back in Europe. Likewise, return migrants could use their new skills acquired in the US labor market. Being able to handle new technology and being accustomed to faster production were qualifications that were in demand in a lot of industrializing European regions.
The majority of so called “New Immigrants” from Southern and Southeastern Europe crossed the Atlantic to seek employment in the growing industrial sector. The rapid process of industrialization in the USA brought about extensive changes in the labor market. From the 1870s on, the development of mines and factories outpaced agriculture as the most dynamic part of the US economy.99 Unlike the European migrants from the middle of the century up to the 1880s who sought land, the newcomers from East-Central Europe found job opportunities in heavy industry, mining, and construction. Since wages were much higher in the US, their goal was to save as much money as possible and return to Europe after two to five years.100
There were two separate waves of transatlantic migration from Austria-Hungary. The first started around the middle of the nineteenth century in Bohemia and in Vorarlberg and reached its high point in the 1880s.101 The second accelerated after the 1890s and involved migrants mainly from Galicia and the Hungarian counties with a Slovak-speaking majority. We give a detailed description of these different transatlantic patterns in Chapter Four. No data on the ethnic breakdown of return migration is available for Austria-Hungary, but at the beginning of the twentieth century, Europeans who crossed the Atlantic were asked if they had been in the US before. According to the ships’ passenger lists, Czech-speaking migrants from Bohemia and Moravia, as well as Jews from Austria-Hungary, had low rates of multiple crossing at about 10 percent.102 The ratio of multiple crossings was also especially low among European Jews. Although East European Jews were often persecuted and suffered discrimination, up to 20 percent chose to go back to Europe regardless. Mark Wyman mentions the story of a Galician Jew who saw the coming back of his American uncle around 1900 as part of the traditional custom.103
The temporary character of labor migration patterns to the US after 1890 is demonstrated by the high number of multiple trips taken by Slovaks; about 40 percent of Slovak-speaking people in our sample of ship passenger lists of 1910 went back and forth between the Hungarian Kingdom and the US.104 Although female and male Poles and Slovaks arriving in the US after the 1890s found employment in the same newly-developed factories and numerous sweatshops, the ratio of Slovaks in the 1910 sample that crossed the Atlantic several times was twice as high as that of Polish US migrants. Likewise, in 1910, multiple transatlantic crossings were especially high among Croats and Slovenes. These South Slavic migrants from Austria-Hungary were overwhelmingly men, many of them married, who came to the US to find work in the steel factories and mines in Pennsylvania, as well as on the Iron Range in Minnesota. After working under harsh conditions in the US for a few years, many of them decided to go back.105 But not all of them stayed in Europe after returning: While some might have gone back to find a spouse in Austria-Hungary and made their way back to America as a married couple, others did not succeed as a return migrant in Europe and therefore decided to go back again to the US.
In comparison to men, women were much less likely to return or to go back and forth between Europe and the Americas several times. Although US labor markets differed for men and women, job opportunities for women had increased as well by the end of the nineteenth century. They either found employment as industrial laborers, mainly in textiles but also in cigar-making and other factories, or as domestic servants in the growing number of middle-class households in the new American cities. Because south and south-eastern Europe, in particular, offered fewer job opportunities for female laborers, a return might have involved a sharp decline in their economic standing.106 Besides, at the beginning of the twentieth century, the population of the United States in the 18–30 age group had a clear male majority, with a high number of single men forming a “lucrative” marriage market. Unlike the large number of married men, young and single women were more likely to leave Europe with expectations of settling in a new continent and starting their own families. According to Marita Krauss, the decision of young women to move on their own can also be interpreted as a process of replacing old, mostly patriarchal traditions by a new way of living. Many of these women did not return because coming home implied a return to patriarchy.107

At the beginning of the twentieth century, Europeans were well informed about the economic conditions overseas. Just as the ethnic press in America kept the migrants informed about developments in Europe, the transfer of information went in the opposite direction as well. American newspapers for migrants made their way to Europe, and the European press published information on the conditions in the US. In this way, the newspapers enabled migrants to plan and manage their (return) migrations.108 If there was an economic downturn in the US, the number of Europeans crossing the Atlantic went down. Figure 2.4, based on return-migration records from the Hungarian statistical office, compares the number of migrants and return migrants from the Hungarian Kingdom with the number of unemployed people in the Unites States of America from 1899 to 1913.
From 1899 through 1904, the number of Hungarian US migrants rose constantly, but the increase of return migrants to the Hungarian Kingdom was even steeper. The highest rate of movements to the US occurred between 1905 and 1907 although the unemployment rate increased in 1906 and culminated in a downturn of the US economy in 1907–1908. The calendar year 1908 was a year of retrenchment as migration fell to under 50,000 persons, down from the more than 200,000 who had departed in 1907.109 Indeed, return migration from the US exceeded out-migration in the Felvídek/Horné Uhorsko counties of the Kingdom (Upper Hungary, today part of the Slovak Republic), the source of so much migration in the 1890s and during the boom that ended in 1907. Economic recovery in the United States in 1909 prompted a rise in renewed out-migration from the Kingdom, but through the pre-war period, the numbers never again came close to the levels of 1905–1907. The depression of 1908 permanently reduced the number of migrants from the Hungarian Kingdom. After the US labor market recovered, Hungarian migration went back to the old patterns of 1899 to 1904 and never was as high as in 1907 whereas the number of returnees stayed much higher. Numbers from the Hungarian census for Torontál County tell us that a mere 216 people left for America in 1899, just 268 in 1901, but by 1905, the number had soared to 6,715 migrants, and two years later in 1907, tripled to 17,558 persons, nearly 3 percent of the total population of the county. Then, in 1908, when the US economy crashed, only 2,403 persons left for America. By 1911, out-migration from Torontál had steadied at about 4,000 and in 1913, the last full year for statistics, 3,550 persons migrated to America.110 Although there was a close connection between the ratio of unemployment in the US and migration from the Hungarian Kingdom, the ratio of returns only mirrored unemployment in 1908, while during other years men and women returned for various reasons as mentioned above. Again, the ethnic press in the US facilitated their decisions as it kept migrants up to date even on details like local cattle markets and weather conditions in the migrants’ home countries.
Migrants from Austria-Hungary exercised the freedom to move, and move again, within its territory, within Europe, within the US, and across the North Atlantic. The freedom to cross the Atlantic came to a sudden end shortly after the June 28, 1914 assassination of the Archduke Ferdinand and his wife at Sarajevo. The 1914 report of the US Commissioner of Immigration tracked the changes in “alien arrivals” in the summer of 1914 compared to one and two years earlier. In July 1913, more than 157,000 migrants arrived at US ports; in August 1913, more than 146,000 and in September of that year, more than 159,000 did so. In 1914, by contrast, the numbers dropped to fewer than 75,000 in July, 15,607 during the first six days of August before the British imposed a blockade of Central Powers seaports. Thereafter, migration to US ports for the rest of August and all of September fell to only one-third of the numbers given for the same months of the summer and early autumn of 1913.111 In the whole of fiscal year of 1915 (July 1, 1914–June 30, 1915), the Immigration Bureau counted 326,700 arrivals and 204,074 departures; the first figure was only one-fourth the rate of the fiscal year of 1914, and the second rate was two-thirds as high as the numbers for the fiscal year of 1914. By the end of the war, in American record-keeping terms, the fiscal years of 1918 and 1919, the arrival of migrants was almost completely off-set by the departure of migrants, and each at only about 200,000 per year, not even one-sixth the level of arrivals in the last pre-war year.112
Although the US was a neutral power in the World War until April 1917, the effects of the global conflict on international migration were felt nearly immediately after the start of the war. The freedom that migrants from Austria-Hungary enjoyed in working and living on two continents ended abruptly, never to be restored. Even before America entered the war, Congress sought to tighten the admission of new migrants by requiring a literacy test for those 16 years and older, beginning on May 1, 1917.113 Still, some expected a return to the patterns prevailing before July 1914. According to the Commissioner of Immigration’s 1920 report about the effects of the war, “the formerly large annual exodus to Austria-Hungary, Russia, and other eastern European countries almost entirely ceased.” He continued, “if normal conditions had continued during the last five years it may be presumed that approximately 1,500,000 aliens would have returned to Europe, instead of the 530,000 who actually did return. It is natural to suppose that many whose home-going has thus been deferred will depart whenever steamship facilities are available … [R]eports have reached the Department, however, which indicate the disturbed conditions prevailing in Europe have led many to postpone if not abandon that purpose.”114 Return migration did recover to more than 288,000 in the fiscal year of 1920 and to almost one-quarter of a million persons the next year. However, additional immigration restrictions passed by Congress in 1921 and 1924 discouraged return migration, if only because migrants could not be sure that they would be re-admitted to the US if they came back.115

Conclusion

This chapter is devoted to the manifold directions of spatial mobility. A lot of different migration paths were open to inhabitants of late Austria-Hungary. People moved over shorter and longer distances inside Imperial Austria and the Kingdom of Hungary; they looked for work in foreign countries closer or further away from home, or they crossed the Atlantic to the Americas. In doing so, their moves were not irreversible. On the contrary, many migrants chose to return to their place of origin. Given the high number of back-and-forth movements of inhabitants of Austria-Hungary, we have to question the usefulness of dichotomous terms such as “emigration regions” as opposed to “immigration regions.” Numerous migrants moved within agricultural areas, and cities had high numbers of out-migration during the period of industrialization as well.
Regional mobility is not a phenomenon of modernity and in no way is it unidirectional from rural to urban areas. Since more and more studies have shown that population mobility was higher in the past than today, we have to question the novelty of our contemporary “mobile society.” Neither modernization, nor industrialization, nor urbanization have proven to be the trigger of so called “mass migrations.” As has been tested in an earlier study on Imperial Austria, income mattered, though not in the way a simple income differential or wage gaps between Central Europe and the US would have it. People did not move to the US from the poorest areas; income mattered to people above a certain wage level. Income differentials are a necessary, but not a sufficient condition for migration.116 While Europeans were highly mobile long before the modern era, migration rates jumped after 1850. Europe saw a massive population increase during the second half of the nineteenth century. Therefore, the absolute number of migrating people increased as well, but preliminary studies have shown that this increase was not caused by population growth, and the jump in migration rates after 1850 is still challenged by recent research.117 However, rising migration rates were not so much caused by industrialization or urbanization, but should be considered primarily as an acceleration of international long-distance mobility, due to faster and cheaper means of transportation.118
While historical migration research, until recently, was dominated by spectacular transatlantic crossings, in late nineteenth century Europe, most migrants moved within the continent. Transatlantic migration had therefore virtually no impact on some parts of Austria-Hungary: Few people crossed the borders of the political district or county they were born in, and many of those who did came from or went to a neighboring province. Seasonal laborers from Galicia went to the German Reich, to the Scandinavian countries, to France and south to the Hungarian Kingdom, trying to find jobs in agriculture as well as in newly developed factories. Some of these migration paths, such as the Sachsengängerei, already had a long tradition and were well known while new routes emerged during extensive industrialization. Even inhabitants of smaller communities chose different routes, as has been shown in the example of the Polish Roman-Catholic population of Western Galicia. According to Dirk Hoerder, there was always a “range of destinations from which potential migrants selected the one that best suited their aspirations.”119 And most of these migration patterns were circular rather than permanent. Central-European migrants were not aimless or clueless wanderers; on the contrary, most often they had accurate information about their destinations.
Migrations are ongoing processes, shaped by the social, economic, and cultural frameworks of human societies. Regional mobility is a phenomenon of all human periods and migration rates were high in pre-modern Europe. Inhabitants of expanding cities, as well as rural dwellers, took part in the extensive process of spatial mobility.120 Based on numerous studies, we now know that previously accepted assumptions about the stability of the peasant community are wrong; instead, scholars have documented the high regional mobility in Europe even in preindustrial times.121 In short, people have always migrated according to seasonal, temporary, rural-rural, rural-urban, urban-rural, and urban-urban migration patterns, and they have emigrated from and immigrated into Europe.122 However, while much research is devoted to spectacular long distance movements, most migrants moved over short distances.123
